Now I have everything I need. I have the actual `src/proxy.ts` file, the full password-gate architecture, the EAP-061 and EAP-079 anti-patterns, and the ENG-097 incident. Let me provide the definitive diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

You are hitting **two layered problems** that compound each other when upgrading from Next.js 15 → 16. Here's the full picture:

---

### Problem 1 — The Filename: `proxy.ts` is Not `middleware.ts` (Primary Cause)

Looking directly at `src/proxy.ts`, the critical issue is the **filename itself**. Next.js middleware only auto-loads from a file named exactly `middleware.ts` (or `middleware.js`) at either the project root or inside `src/`. The file `src/proxy.ts` is **never invoked automatically by Next.js** — it is just a regular module that exports a function and a `config` object that nobody calls.

In Next.js 15, this may have appeared to "work" if there was an explicit import or call somewhere (e.g., from an actual `middleware.ts` that `import { proxy } from "./proxy"` then called it). In Next.js 16, any implicit plumbing that forwarded the call was likely removed or the `middleware.ts` entry point itself was deleted/renamed during the upgrade.

**The `config.matcher` you see at the bottom of `src/proxy.ts` is completely inert** — Next.js only reads `matcher` from a file it treats as middleware, i.e., from `src/middleware.ts` or `middleware.ts` at root. Exporting `config` from an arbitrary module does nothing.

---

### Problem 2 — The `/api/*` Allowlist Means Auth Is Intentionally Bypassed for ALL `/api/internal/*` (Secondary Cause, **EAP-079**)

Even if the middleware were wired up correctly, look at lines 14–16 of `src/proxy.ts`:

```typescript
// Allow Payload CMS admin and API routes through (Payload has its own auth)
if (pathname.startsWith("/admin") || pathname.startsWith("/api")) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}
```

The allowlist passes **all** `/api/*` paths through unconditionally — including your new `/api/internal/*` routes. The comment says "Payload has its own auth," which is true for `/api/payload-specific-routes`, but `/api/internal/*` are your own custom route handlers and they do **not** have independent auth. This is a classic **EAP-079** proxy allowlist gap: a new path namespace was added without auditing whether the existing allowlist over-broadly exempts it.

---

## Root Cause

**Primary:** `src/proxy.ts` is never invoked as Next.js middleware because Next.js only executes the Edge Runtime middleware entrypoint at `src/middleware.ts` (or `<root>/middleware.ts`). There is no `src/middleware.ts` — the auth logic is a dead module. This is a variant of **EAP-061** (*File Conventions Leak Across Monorepo Apps via turbopack.root*) — the inverse: a file uses the right structural conventions (exports a function + `config`) but the wrong **filename**, so the framework never picks it up.

**Secondary:** The `/api` catch-all in the allowlist (EAP-079) would bypass auth for `/api/internal/*` even if the file were correctly named.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Create the real middleware entrypoint

**`src/middleware.ts`** (new file):

```typescript
// src/middleware.ts
// This is the Next.js Edge Runtime entrypoint — MUST be named middleware.ts.
// Do not add business logic here; delegate to proxy.ts so the logic
// stays testable and co-located with the password-gate architecture.
export { proxy as middleware, config } from "@/proxy";
```

This single re-export wires `src/proxy.ts` into the Next.js middleware lifecycle. The framework now reads the `config.matcher` from it and calls `proxy()` on every matched request.

> **Why a re-export instead of renaming?** `src/proxy.ts` is explicitly called out in `AGENTS.md` guardrail-engineering-23 as a protected file with its own architectural reference (the password-gate skill). Keeping the logic in `proxy.ts` and only the entrypoint in `middleware.ts` preserves that separation and makes the proxy independently testable.

---

### Step 2 — Tighten the `/api` allowlist to exclude `/api/internal/*`

**`src/proxy.ts`** — change lines 14–16:

```typescript
// BEFORE (over-broad — passes ALL /api/* through including /api/internal/*)
if (pathname.startsWith("/admin") || pathname.startsWith("/api")) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}
```

```typescript
// AFTER — only pass through Payload's own API namespace
if (
  pathname.startsWith("/admin") ||
  pathname.startsWith("/api/payload") ||   // Payload REST API
  pathname.startsWith("/api/graphql") ||   // Payload GraphQL
  pathname === "/api/health"               // any safe public health-check
) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}
// NOTE: /api/internal/* is NOT in the allowlist — it goes through session auth below
```

If Payload CMS uses a different route prefix in your project, verify by checking `src/payload.config.ts` for the `routes.api` setting (default is `/api`). The goal is to allowlist only the Payload-owned paths, not the entire `/api` namespace.

---

### Step 3 — Add `/api/internal/*` explicit auth (defense-in-depth)

Even with the middleware correctly gating `/api/internal/*`, add a thin guard inside each internal route handler as a defense-in-depth layer. The proxy header is already available:

```typescript
// src/app/api/internal/[...route]/route.ts
import { headers } from "next/headers";
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";

export async function GET(request: Request) {
  const company = (await headers()).get("x-company");
  if (!company) {
    // Should never reach here if proxy is working, but belt-and-suspenders
    return NextResponse.json({ error: "Unauthorized" }, { status: 401 });
  }
  // ... handler logic
}
```

The `x-company` header is set by `proxy.ts` on every request that passes session verification (see the last block of `src/proxy.ts`). If it is absent, the request was not proxied through a valid session.

---

### Step 4 — Verify the matcher covers `/api/internal/*`

The current `config.matcher` in `src/proxy.ts` is:

```typescript
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|sitemap.xml|robots.txt).*)",
  ],
};
```

This regex-based matcher **does** include `/api/internal/*` (it only excludes `_next/static`, `_next/image`, and root metadata files). So the matcher is fine — the only issue was the file not being loaded at all.

---

## Verification Protocol

Follow the password-gate testing protocol after these changes:

```bash
# 1. Hard restart — middleware changes require a full server restart
rm -rf .next && npm run dev

# 2. Verify middleware is loaded — Next.js 16 logs middleware on startup
#    Look for: "○ Middleware  src/middleware.ts"

# 3. Test /api/internal/* without a session cookie
curl -v http://localhost:4000/api/internal/some-route
# Expected: 302 redirect to /for/welcome (NOT a 200 from the route handler)

# 4. Test /api/ (Payload routes) still work
curl -v http://localhost:4000/api/globals/site-config
# Expected: 200 (Payload API, should pass through)

# 5. Test with a valid session
curl -v --cookie "portfolio_session=<valid-cookie>" \
  http://localhost:4000/api/internal/some-route
# Expected: 200 from the route handler, with x-company header forwarded
```

---

## Principle

> **Next.js middleware is a filename contract, not an export contract.** Exporting a function called `middleware` or a `config` with a `matcher` does nothing unless the file is named exactly `middleware.ts` and sits at `src/` or the project root. Any other filename is just a regular module. — Closes the gap cataloged in **EAP-061** (file convention assumptions in a monorepo) and **EAP-079** (proxy allowlist gaps when new path namespaces are added).
